To create a Discord bot that uses Discord.js v14 and has a slash command for banning users, you will first need to set up your bot on the Discord Developer Portal and invite it to your server. Then, use the following steps and code snippet to implement the ban command:

1. **Setup Your Project**: If you haven't already, initialize a new Node.js project and install `discord.js` v14.
   ```
   npm init -y
   npm install discord.js@14
   ```

2. **Create Your Bot File**: Let's name it `bot.js`. This is where you'll write your bot's code.

3. **Bot Code**:
   ```js
   const { Client, GatewayIntentBits } = require('discord.js');
   const { REST } = require('@discordjs/rest');
   const { Routes } = require('discord-api-types/v10');

   const clientId = 'YOUR_CLIENT_ID';
   const guildId = 'YOUR_GUILD_ID';
   const token = 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN';

   const client = new Client({ intents: [GatewayIntentBits.Guilds] });

   const commands = [
     {
       name: 'ban',
       description: 'Bans a user from the server',
       options: [{
         type: 6, // USER type
         name: 'user',
         description: 'The user to ban',
         required: true,
       }],
     }
   ];

   const rest = new REST({ version: '10' }).setToken(token);

   (async () => {
     try {
       console.log('Started refreshing application (/) commands.');

       await rest.put(
         Routes.applicationGuildCommands(clientId, guildId),
         { body: commands },
       );

       console.log('Successfully reloaded application (/) commands.');
     } catch (error) {
       console.error(error);
     }
   })();

   client.once('ready', () => {
     console.log(`Logged in as ${client.user.tag}!`);
   });

   client.on('interactionCreate', async interaction => {
     if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

     const { commandName } = interaction;

     if (commandName === 'ban') {
       const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
       const member = interaction.guild.members.cache.get(user.id);

       if (!member) {
         await interaction.reply({ content: 'User not found in this server.', ephemeral: true });
         return;
       }

       member.ban()
         .then(() => interaction.reply({ content: `${user.tag} has been banned.`, ephemeral: true }))
         .catch(error => interaction.reply({ content: `Failed to ban ${user.tag}: ${error}`, ephemeral: true }));
     }
   });

   client.login(token);
   ```

4. **Final Steps**:
   - Replace `'YOUR_CLIENT_ID'`, `'YOUR_GUILD_ID'`, and `'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN'` with your bot's client ID, your server's guild ID, and your bot token, respectively.
   - Run your bot using `node bot.js`.

This code snippet initiates a Discord bot that listens for the `/ban` command. When executed, it attempts to ban the specified user from the server, handling both success and error cases gracefully. Make sure you have the necessary permissions on Discord to invite and allow the bot to ban users.

Certainly! Below is a C++ function that takes a reference to a `std::string` containing basic Markdown formatted text and returns a `std::string` containing the equivalent HTML formatted text. This function handles the conversion of headers, bold text, italic text, and links. Please note that Markdown and HTML are both quite extensive and support a large number of features. This function covers a basic subset for the purpose of the example.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::string html = markdown;

    // Convert Markdown headers to HTML headers
    std::regex rHeaders("^#{1,6}.*$", std::regex_constants::multiline);
    html = std::regex_replace(html, rHeaders, [](const std::smatch& m) {
        std::string headerTag = m.str();
        size_t headerLevel = headerTag.find_first_not_of('#');
        return "<h" + std::to_string(headerLevel) + ">" + headerTag.substr(headerLevel + 1) + "</h" + std::to_string(headerLevel) + ">";
    });

    // Convert Markdown bold text **text** to HTML <strong>text</strong>
    std::regex rBold("\\*\\*(.*?)\\*\\*");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, rBold, "<strong>$1</strong>");

    // Convert Markdown italic text *text* to HTML <em>text</em>
    std::regex rItalic("\\*(.*?)\\*");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, rItalic, "<em>$1</em>");

    // Convert Markdown links [text](url) to HTML <a href="url">text</a>
    std::regex rLink("\\[(.*?)\\]\\((.*?)\\)");
    html = std::regex_replace(html, rLink, "<a href=\"$2\">$1</a>");

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdownText = R"(
# Header 1
## Header 2
Some **bold** text and *italic* text.
Also, a link to [Google](https://google.com).
)";

    std::string htmlText = markdownToHtml(markdownText);
    std::cout << htmlText << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

In the `markdownToHtml` function:

1. We use regex to match the Markdown patterns for headers, bold, italic, and links.
2. We replace the patterns with their respective HTML tags using `std::regex_replace`.
3. We use lambda expressions in `std::regex_replace` to calculate the header level and create the respective tag.
4. The `main` function provides a simple usage example.

Remember to enable C++11 support if you're using an older compiler since regex and to_string() are part of C++11.

