In LaTeX, an automated table of contents (ToC) is produced by placing the `\tableofcontents` command in the location where you want the ToC to appear. LaTeX handles the generation of the ToC by considering all the sectional commands (`\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, etc.) you have used in the document.

Below is an example LaTeX document code that illustrates how to generate a table of contents, including the preamble with document class and essential packages, and the body containing sections. Make sure you run LaTeX twice on your document; the first run gathers all the headings and page numbers, and the second run updates the ToC with the correct information.

```latex
\documentclass[10pt]{article}

% Loading packages that may be necessary for formatting or functionality
\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc} % Package for input encoding
\usepackage{hyperref}       % Package for creating hyperlinks in the document

\begin{document}

\title{Example Document}
\author{Author's Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

% This command adds Table of Contents based on sections
\tableofcontents

% Adds a clear page so the content starts from the next page
\clearpage

\section{Introduction}
This is the introduction of the document.

\subsection{Background}
The background section can have its own subsections and content.

\subsection{Objective}
The objective of your document will be outlined here.

\section{Methodology}
Describe your methods here.

\subsection{Data Collection}
Information about how data was collected.

\subsection{Data Analysis}
Discuss how the data was analyzed.

\section{Results}
Present your results here.

\subsection{Data Representation}
Data can be represented in various forms.

\subsection{Statistical Analysis}
Detail any statistical analysis that was performed.

\section{Conclusion}
Conclude the findings of your document here.

% Adding additional sections/subsections will automatically update the Table of Contents
\end{document}
```

In this example, the `\section` and `\subsection` commands are what LaTeX uses to determine what entries to include in the Table of Contents. The `hyperref` package is used to make items in the ToC clickable (not necessary but quite useful for navigation in the resulting PDF document).

Remember that the ToC will be updated to reflect the correct page numbers and sections when LaTeX is run twice.

